ultural mechanisms that support the persistent male domination of engineering, and analyzing the laboratory as a fictive kin group that reproduces gender asymmetries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 4aAnthropology -- Science, Technology, and Medical Anthropology. 4aAnthropology -- Theory and History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aFleck, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHess, David J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361937140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503619371423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503619371/original  a978-3-11-070420-4  Stanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles